======================================================================
  STEP 6: ROBUSTNESS TEST — SUMMARY REPORT
  Generated by step6_robustness_test.py
======================================================================

1. WHAT THIS STEP DOES
--------------------------------------------------
  Step 6 tests whether the failure-point thresholds
  from Step 5 are robust to changes in cost structure.

  Method: Re-run the FE-only sweep (50 spread levels)
  under 4 different shortage penalty levels, keeping
  all other parameters frozen.

  Total experiments: 200
  Spread levels tested: 50
  Cost scenarios tested: 4


2. COST SCENARIOS TESTED
--------------------------------------------------
  Scenario                   Penalty    Price    Ratio
  ------------------------- -------- -------- --------
  S1: Low ($1)              $     1 $    10     10%
  S2: Baseline ($3)         $     3 $    10     30%
  S3: High ($5)             $     5 $    10     50%
  S4: Very High ($8)        $     8 $    10     80%


3. THRESHOLD COMPARISON ACROSS SCENARIOS
--------------------------------------------------
  (FE spread value where each criterion triggers)

  Criterion                      $1         $3         $5         $8    Direction
  ---------------------- ---------- ---------- ---------- ---------- ------------
  %VSS > 2%                  0.1817     0.1778     0.1747     0.1712       ← LEFT
  %VSS > 1.5%                0.1037     0.1008     0.0964     0.0891       ← LEFT
  Service gap > 1            0.1792     0.1792     0.1792     0.1792       — FLAT
  Service gap > 3            0.2149     0.2149     0.2149     0.2149       — FLAT
  VSS > $150                 0.2086     0.2028     0.1983     0.1931       ← LEFT


4. KEY FINDING — THRESHOLD DIRECTION
--------------------------------------------------
  As the shortage penalty INCREASES:
    -> Thresholds move LEFT (lower FE spread)
    -> Stochastic planning becomes necessary SOONER
    -> Deterministic planning is adequate for a
       NARROWER range of yield uncertainty

  As the shortage penalty DECREASES:
    -> Thresholds move RIGHT (higher FE spread)
    -> Deterministic planning remains adequate for
       a WIDER range of yield uncertainty


5. PRACTITIONER GUIDANCE VALUES
--------------------------------------------------
  When should you invest in stochastic planning?
  (Based on %VSS > 2% criterion)

  If penalty = 10% of price:
    Switch when FE spread > 0.18  (yields wider than [0.693, 1.000])

  If penalty = 30% of price:
    Switch when FE spread > 0.18  (yields wider than [0.697, 1.000])

  If penalty = 50% of price:
    Switch when FE spread > 0.17  (yields wider than [0.700, 1.000])

  If penalty = 80% of price:
    Switch when FE spread > 0.17  (yields wider than [0.704, 1.000])


6. CONNECTION TO STEP 7
--------------------------------------------------
  Step 7 will synthesize Steps 5 and 6 into a single
  decision rule of the form:

    "If your FE yield spread exceeds X and your
     shortage penalty is at least Y% of selling price,
     invest in stochastic planning. Otherwise,
     average-yield planning is sufficient."

  The threshold values from this step provide the
  (X, Y) pairs that define the decision boundary.
  Figure 3 (step6_fig3_boundary_map.png) is a visual
  prototype of this decision map.


7. CONNECTION TO THE LITERATURE
--------------------------------------------------
  Rashidi et al. use a penalty of ~10% of selling
  price in their test case. Our S1 scenario ($1
  penalty on $10 price) matches this ratio. The
  finding that lower penalties push thresholds
  rightward is consistent with the theoretical
  prediction: when shortfalls cost less, the
  asymmetry between over-producing and under-
  producing is smaller, so the deterministic
  model's 'average' plan is less costly.

  This is the second core contribution of the
  ITC 2026 paper: not just where the threshold is
  (Step 5), but how it depends on cost structure
  (Step 6).

